name: UInterchangeFactoryBaseNode
doc:
This struct is used to store and retrieve key-value attributes. The attributes are stored in a generic FAttributeStorage that serializes the values in a TArray64<uint8>.
See UE::Interchange::EAttributeTypes to know the supported template types.
This is an abstract class. This is the base class of the Interchange node graph format; all classes in this format should derive from this class.

methods.name: AddFactoryDependencyUid
methods.doc: Add one dependency to this object.

methods.name: GetCustomReferenceObject
methods.doc: Return the custom ReferenceObject: the UObject this factory node has created.

methods.name: GetCustomSubPath
methods.doc: Return the custom sub-path under PackageBasePath where the assets will be created.

methods.name: GetFactoryDependencies
methods.doc: Retrieve the dependencies for this object.

methods.name: GetFactoryDependenciesCount
methods.doc: Retrieve the number of factory dependencies for this object.

methods.name: GetFactoryDependency
methods.doc: Retrieve one dependency for this object.

methods.name: RemoveFactoryDependencyUid
methods.doc: Remove one dependency from this object.

methods.name: SetCustomReferenceObject
methods.doc: Set the custom ReferenceObject: the UObject this factory node has created.

methods.name: SetCustomSubPath
methods.doc: Set the custom sub-path under PackageBasePath where the assets will be created.

methods.name: SetForceNodeReimport
methods.doc: Allow the creation of the Unreal object even if it has been previously deleted in the editor.

methods.name: SetSkipNodeImport
methods.doc: Add the skip node attribute. Use this function to cancel the creation of the Unreal asset. See ShouldSkipNodeImport for more documentation.

methods.name: ShouldForceNodeReimport
methods.doc:
Return whether or not an object should be created even if it has been deleted in the editor.
Return false by default.

methods.name: ShouldSkipNodeImport
methods.doc:
Return true if this node should skip the factory import process, or false otherwise.
Nodes can be in a situation where we have to skip the import process because we cannot import the associated asset for multiple reasons. For example:
- An asset can already exist and represents a different type (UClass).
- An asset can already exist and is being compiled.
- An asset can already exist and is being imported by another concurrent import task (such as a user importing multiple files at the same time in the same content folder).

methods.name: UnsetForceNodeReimport
methods.doc: Disallow the creation of the Unreal object if it has been previously deleted in the editor.

methods.name: UnsetSkipNodeImport
methods.doc: Remove the skip node attribute. See ShouldSkipNodeImport for more documentation.
